# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: roda-ruby
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:roda-ruby/documentation] Federico Iachetti has generously put his *Mastering Roda* book under the Commons Attribution 4.0 International License, and posted a publicly accessible online version.
[src:roda-ruby/documentation] The book has been updated and now is kept up to date with changes to Roda.
[src:roda-ruby/documentation] If you would like to improve the book, please submit a merge request.
[src:roda-ruby/documentation] Plugins are a very important part of Roda, since by design Roda has a very small core.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] Rack is used by many Ruby web frameworks and libraries, such as Ruby on Rails and Sinatra.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] Many Ruby applications are called "rack-compliant".
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] Rack has inspired similar frameworks in JavaScript (jack.js), Clojure, Perl (Plack), Common Lisp (Clack), and .NET (OWIN).
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] The characteristics of a Rack application is that the application object responds to the call method.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] The call method takes in the environment object as argument and returns the Rack response object.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] In case the application is being used as a middleware, the environment can have objects that would provide session information, logging capabilities, information on the size of the data that can be used for read and writes etc.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] In addition to these, the server can store their own data in the environment.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] The rack server object returns a response which contains three parts: the status, headers and the body.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] Rack::Response provides a convenient interface to create a Rack response.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] The class Rack::Response is defined in lib/rack/response.rb.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] To use the Response class, instantiate it from the middleware layer down the stack.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] Rack makes it easy to add a chain of middleware components between the application and the web server.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] Multiple middleware components can be used in the rack which modifies the request/response before handing it over to the next component.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] The Rack server adds multiple middle middleware by default for the functionalities like showing exception with all the details, validating the request and responses according to the Rack spec etc.
[src:roda-ruby/rack-web-server-interface] The server for the above code can be initiated using "rackup helloWorld.ru" and can be accessed at http://localhost:9292/ The default port used by the Rack application is 9292.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In packet switching networks, routing is the higher-level decision-making that directs network packets from their source toward their destination through intermediate network nodes by specific packet forwarding mechanisms.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Packet forwarding is the transit of network packets from one network interface to another.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Intermediate nodes are typically network hardware devices such as routers, gateways, firewalls, or switches.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] General-purpose computers also forward packets and perform routing, although they have no specially optimized hardware for the task.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] The routing process usually directs forwarding on the basis of routing tables.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Routing tables maintain a record of the routes to various network destinations.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Routing tables may be specified by an administrator, learned by observing network traffic or built with the assistance of routing protocols.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Routing, in a narrower sense of the term, often refers to IP routing and is contrasted with bridging.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] IP routing assumes that network addresses are structured and that similar addresses imply proximity within the network.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Structured addresses allow a single routing table entry to represent the route to a group of devices.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In large networks, structured addressing (routing, in the narrow sense) outperforms unstructured addressing (bridging).
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Routing has become the dominant form of addressing on the Internet.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Bridging is still widely used within local area networks.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Unicast is the dominant form of message delivery on the Internet.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] This article focuses on unicast routing algorithms.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] With static routing, small networks may use manually configured routing tables.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Larger networks have complex topologies that can change rapidly, making the manual construction of routing tables unfeasible.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Nevertheless, most of the public switched telephone network (PSTN) uses pre-computed routing tables, with fallback routes if the most direct route becomes blocked (see routing in the PSTN).
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Dynamic routing attempts to solve this problem by constructing routing tables automatically, based on information carried by routing protocols, allowing the network to act nearly autonomously in avoiding network failures and blockages.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Examples of dynamic-routing protocols and algorithms include Routing Information Protocol (RIP), Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) and Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Distance vector algorithms use the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] This approach assigns a *cost* number to each of the links between each node in the network.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Nodes send information from point A to point B via the path that results in the lowest *total cost* (i.e., the sum of the costs of the links between the nodes used).
[src:roda-ruby/routing] When a node first starts, it only knows of its immediate neighbors and the direct cost involved in reaching them.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] The neighboring nodes examine this information and compare it to what they already know; anything that represents an improvement on what they already have, they insert in their own table.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Over time, all the nodes in the network discover the best next hop and total cost for all destinations.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] When a network node goes down, any nodes that used it as their next hop discard the entry and convey the updated routing information to all adjacent nodes, which in turn repeat the process.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Eventually, all the nodes in the network receive the updates and discover new paths to all the destinations that do not involve the down node.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] When applying link-state algorithms, a graphical map of the network is the fundamental data used for each node.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] To produce its map, each node floods the entire network with information about the other nodes it can connect to.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Each node then independently assembles this information into a map.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Using this map, each router independently determines the least-cost path from itself to every other node using a standard shortest paths algorithm such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] The result is a tree graph rooted at the current node, such that the path through the tree from the root to any other node is the least-cost path to that node.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] This tree then serves to construct the routing table, which specifies the best next hop to get from the current node to any other node.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] A link-state routing algorithm optimized for mobile ad hoc networks is the optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR).
[src:roda-ruby/routing] OLSR is proactive; it uses Hello and Topology Control (TC) messages to discover and disseminate link-state information through the mobile ad hoc network.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Using Hello messages, each node discovers 2-hop neighbor information and elects a set of *multipoint relays* (MPRs).
[src:roda-ruby/routing] MPRs distinguish OLSR from other link-state routing protocols.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Distance vector and link-state routing are both intra-domain routing protocols.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] They are used inside an autonomous system, but not between autonomous systems.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Both of these routing protocols become intractable in large networks and cannot be used in inter-domain routing.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Distance vector routing is subject to instability if there are more than a few hops in the domain.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Link-state routing needs significant resources to calculate routing tables.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] It also creates heavy traffic due to flooding.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Path-vector routing is used for inter-domain routing.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] It is similar to distance vector routing.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Path-vector routing assumes that one node (there can be many) in each autonomous system acts on behalf of the entire autonomous system.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] This node is called the *speaker node.* The speaker node creates a routing table and advertises it to neighboring speaker nodes in neighboring autonomous systems.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] The idea is the same as distance vector routing, except that only speaker nodes in each autonomous system can communicate with each other.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] The speaker node advertises the path, not the metric, of the nodes in its autonomous system or other autonomous systems.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] The path-vector routing algorithm is similar to the distance vector algorithm in the sense that each border router advertises the destinations it can reach to its neighboring router.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] However, instead of advertising networks in terms of a destination and the distance to that destination, networks are advertised as destination addresses and path descriptions to reach those destinations.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] The path, expressed in terms of the domains (or confederations) traversed so far, is carried in a special path attribute that records the sequence of routing domains through which the reachability information has passed.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] A route is defined as a pairing between a destination and the attributes of the path to that destination, thus the name, path-vector routing.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] The routers receive a vector that contains paths to a set of destinations.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Path selection involves applying a routing metric to multiple routes to select (or predict) the best route.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Most routing algorithms use only one network path at a time.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Multipath routing and specifically equal-cost multi-path routing techniques enable the use of multiple alternative paths.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In computer networking, the metric is computed by a routing algorithm, and can cover information such as bandwidth, network delay, hop count, path cost, load, maximum transmission unit, reliability, and communication cost.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] The routing table stores only the best possible routes, while link-state or topological databases may store all other information as well.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] *Metric*: When comparing routes learned via the same routing protocol, a lower metric is preferred.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Metrics cannot be compared between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] *Administrative distance*: When comparing route table entries from different sources, such as different routing protocols and static configuration, a lower administrative distance indicates a more reliable source and thus a preferred route.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Because a routing metric is specific to a given routing protocol, multi-protocol routers must use some external heuristic to select between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Cisco routers, for example, attribute a value known as the administrative distance to each route, where smaller administrative distances indicate routes learned from a protocol assumed to be more reliable.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] A local administrator can set up host-specific routes that provide more control over network usage, permit testing, and better overall security.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] This is useful for debugging network connections or routing tables.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In some small systems, a single central device decides ahead of time the complete path of every packet.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In some other small systems, whichever edge device injects a packet into the network decides ahead of time the complete path of that particular packet.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In either case, the route-planning device needs to know a lot of information about what devices are connected to the network and how they are connected to each other.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Once it has this information, it can use an algorithm such as A* search algorithm to find the best path.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In high-speed systems, there are so many packets transmitted every second that it is infeasible for a single device to calculate the complete path for each and every packet.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Early high-speed systems dealt with this with circuit switching by setting up a path once for the first packet between some source and some destination; later packets between that same source and that same destination continue to follow the same path without recalculating until the circuit teardown.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Later high-speed systems inject packets into the network without any one device ever calculating a complete path for packets.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In large systems, there are so many connections between devices, and those connections change so frequently, that it is infeasible for any one device to even know how all the devices are connected to each other, much less calculate a complete path through them.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Such systems generally use next-hop routing.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Most systems use a deterministic dynamic routing algorithm.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] When a device chooses a path to a particular final destination, that device always chooses the same path to that destination until it receives information that makes it think some other path is better.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] A few routing algorithms do not use a deterministic algorithm to find the best link for a packet to get from its original source to its final destination.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Instead, to avoid congestion hot spots in packet systems, a few algorithms use a randomized algorithm—Valiant's paradigm—that routes a path to a randomly picked intermediate destination, and from there to its true final destination.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In many early telephone switches, a randomizer was often used to select the start of a path through a multistage switching fabric.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Depending on the application for which path selection is performed, different metrics can be used.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] For example, for web requests, one can use minimum latency paths to minimize web page load time, or for bulk data transfers, one can choose the least utilized path to balance load across the network and increase throughput.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] A popular path selection objective is to reduce the average completion times of traffic flows and the total network bandwidth consumption.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Recently, a path selection metric was proposed that computes the total number of bytes scheduled on the edges per path as a selection metric.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] An empirical analysis of several path selection metrics, including this new proposal, has been made available.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In some networks, routing is complicated by the fact that no single entity is responsible for selecting paths; instead, multiple entities are involved in selecting paths or even parts of a single path.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Complications or inefficiency can result if these entities choose paths to optimize their own objectives, which may conflict with the objectives of other participants.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] A classic example involves traffic in a road system, in which each driver picks a path that minimizes their travel time.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] With such routing, the equilibrium routes can be longer than optimal for all drivers.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In particular, Braess's paradox shows that adding a new road can *lengthen* travel times for all drivers.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In a single-agent model used, for example, for routing automated guided vehicles (AGVs) on a terminal, reservations are made for each vehicle to prevent simultaneous use of the same part of an infrastructure.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] This approach is also referred to as context-aware routing.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] The Internet is partitioned into autonomous systems (ASs) such as internet service providers (ISPs), each of which controls routes involving its network.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] First, AS-level paths are selected via the BGP protocol that produces a sequence of ASs through which packets flow.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Each AS may have multiple paths, offered by neighboring ASs, from which to choose.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] These routing decisions often correlate with business relationships with these neighboring ASs, which may be unrelated to path quality or latency.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Second, once an AS-level path has been selected, there are often multiple corresponding router-level paths to choose from.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] This is due, in part, because two ISPs may be connected through multiple connections.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In choosing the single router-level path, it is common practice for each ISP to employ hot-potato routing: sending traffic along the path that minimizes the distance through the ISP's own network—even if that path lengthens the total distance to the destination.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] For example, consider two ISPs, *A* and *B*.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Each has a presence in New York, connected by a fast link with latency 5 ms—and each has a presence in London connected by a 5 ms link.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Suppose both ISPs have trans-Atlantic links that connect their two networks, but *A*'s link has latency 100 ms and *B*'s has latency 120 ms.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] When routing a message from a source in *A*'s London network to a destination in *B*'s New York network, *A* may choose to immediately send the message to *B* in London.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] This saves *A* the work of sending it along an expensive trans-Atlantic link, but causes the message to experience latency 125 ms when the other route would have been 20 ms faster.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Additionally, a similar routing challenge can be observed in cellular networks, where different packets are destined for various endpoints, and each link exhibits varying spectral efficiency.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In this context, the selection of the *optimal* path involves considering latency and packet error rate.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] To address this, multiple independent entities, one for each base station, play a crucial role in path selection while striving to optimize overall network performance.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] A 2003 measurement study of Internet routes found that, between pairs of neighboring ISPs, more than 30% of paths have inflated latency due to hot-potato routing, with 5% of paths being delayed by at least 12 ms.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Inflation due to AS-level path selection, while substantial, was attributed primarily to BGP's lack of a mechanism to directly optimize for latency, rather than to selfish routing policies.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] It was also suggested that, were an appropriate mechanism in place, ISPs would be willing to cooperate to reduce latency rather than use hot-potato routing.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Such a mechanism was later published by the same authors, first for the case of two ISPs and then for the global case.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] As the Internet and IP networks have become mission critical business tools, there has been increased interest in techniques and methods to monitor the routing posture of networks.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Incorrect routing or routing issues cause undesirable performance degradation, flapping or downtime.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Monitoring routing in a network is achieved using route analytics tools and techniques.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] In networks where a logically centralized control is available over the forwarding state, for example, using software-defined networking, routing techniques can be used that aim to optimize global and network-wide performance metrics.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] This has been used by large internet companies that operate many data centers in different geographical locations attached using private optical links, examples of which include Microsoft's Global WAN, Facebook's Express Backbone, and Google's B4.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Global performance metrics to optimize include maximizing network utilization, minimizing traffic flow completion times, maximizing the traffic delivered prior to specific deadlines and reducing the completion times of flows.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] Work on the later over private WAN discusses modeling routing as a graph optimization problem by pushing all the queuing to the end-points.
[src:roda-ruby/routing] The authors also propose a heuristic to solve the problem efficiently while sacrificing negligible performance.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is interpreted, high-level, and dynamically typed; its interpreter uses garbage collection and just-in-time compilation.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It supports multiple programming paradigms, including procedural, object-oriented, and functional programming.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] According to the creator, Ruby was influenced by Perl, Smalltalk, Eiffel, Ada, BASIC, and Lisp.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] According to Matsumoto, Ruby was conceived in 1993.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto described Ruby's design as resembling a simple Lisp language at its core, with an object system like that of Smalltalk, blocks inspired by higher-order functions, and practical utility like that of Perl.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The name "Ruby" originated during an online chat session between Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka on 24 February 1993, before any code had been written.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Two names were initially proposed: "Coral" and "Ruby".
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto chose the latter in a subsequent email to Ishitsuka.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] He also noted that one factor influencing the choice of the name was that a colleague's birthstone was ruby.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The first public release of Ruby 0.95 was announced on Japanese domestic newsgroups on 21 December 1995.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Subsequently, three more versions of Ruby were released in two days.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The release coincided with the launch of the Japanese-language *ruby-list* mailing list, which was the first mailing list for the new language.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Already present at this stage of development were many of the features familiar in later releases of Ruby, including object-oriented design, classes with inheritance, mixins, iterators, closures, exception handling and garbage collection.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] After the release of Ruby 0.95 in 1995, several stable versions of Ruby were released in these years.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In 1997, the first article about Ruby was published on the Web.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In the same year, Matsumoto was hired by netlab.jp to work on Ruby as a full-time developer.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In 1998, the Ruby Application Archive was launched by Matsumoto, along with a simple English-language homepage for Ruby.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In 1999, the first English language mailing list *ruby-talk* began, which signaled a growing interest in the language outside Japan.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In this same year, Matsumoto and Keiju Ishitsuka wrote the first book on Ruby, *The Object-oriented Scripting Language Ruby* (オブジェクト指向スクリプト言語 Ruby), which was published in Japan in October 1999.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It would be followed in the early 2000s by around 20 books on Ruby published in Japanese.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] By 2000, Ruby was more popular than Python in Japan.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In September 2000, the first English language book *Programming Ruby* was printed, which was later freely released to the public, further widening the adoption of Ruby amongst English speakers.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In early 2002, the English-language *ruby-talk* mailing list was receiving more messages than the Japanese-language *ruby-list*, demonstrating Ruby's increasing popularity in the non-Japanese speaking world.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 was initially released in August 2003, was stable for a long time, and was retired in June 2013.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Although deprecated, there is still code based on it.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 is only partially compatible with Ruby 1.9.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 1.8 has been the subject of several industry standards.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It was accepted as a Japanese Industrial Standard (JIS X 3017) in 2011 and an international standard (ISO/IEC 30170) in 2012.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Around 2005, interest in the Ruby language surged in tandem with Ruby on Rails, a web framework written in Ruby.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Rails is frequently credited with increasing awareness of Ruby.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Effective with Ruby 1.9.3, released 31 October 2011, Ruby switched from being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the GPL to being dual-licensed under the Ruby License and the two-clause BSD license.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Adoption of 1.9 was slowed by changes from 1.8 that required many popular third party gems to be rewritten.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.0 was intended to be fully backward compatible with Ruby 1.9.3.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] As of the official 2.0.0 release on 24 February 2013, there were only five known incompatibilities.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Starting with 2.1.0, Ruby's versioning policy changed to be more similar to semantic versioning, although it differs slightly in that minor version increments may be API incompatible.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.2.0 includes speed-ups, bugfixes, and library updates and removes some deprecated APIs.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Most notably, Ruby 2.2.0 introduces changes to memory handling – an incremental garbage collector, support for garbage collection of symbols and the option to compile directly against jemalloc.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It also contains experimental support for using vfork(2) with system() and spawn(), and added support for the Unicode 7.0 specification.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Since version 2.2.1, Ruby MRI performance on PowerPC64 was improved.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Features that were made obsolete or removed include callcc, the DL library, Digest::HMAC, lib/rational.rb, lib/complex.rb, GServer, Logger::Application as well as various C API functions.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.3.0 includes many performance improvements, updates, and bugfixes including changes to Proc#call, Socket and IO use of exception keywords, Thread#name handling, default passive Net::FTP connections, and Rake being removed from stdlib.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 2.4.0 includes performance improvements to hash table, Array#max, Array#min, and instance variable access.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.6.0 include an experimental just-in-time compiler (JIT), and *RubyVM::AbstractSyntaxTree* (experimental).
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] A few notable changes in Ruby 2.7.0 include pattern Matching (experimental), REPL improvements, a compaction GC, and separation of positional and keyword arguments.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0.0 was released on Christmas Day in 2020.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It is known as Ruby 3x3, which signifies that programs would run three times faster in Ruby 3.0 comparing to Ruby 2.0. and some had already been implemented in intermediate releases on the road from 2 to 3.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] To achieve 3x3, Ruby 3 comes with MJIT, and later YJIT, Just-In-Time Compilers, to make programs faster, although they are described as experimental and remain disabled by default (enabled by flags at runtime).
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Another goal of Ruby 3.0 is to improve concurrency and two more utilities Fibre Scheduler, and experimental Ractor facilitate the goal.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ractor is light-weight and thread-safe as it is achieved by exchanging messages rather than shared objects.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.0 introduces RBS language to describe the types of Ruby programs for static analysis.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It is separated from general Ruby programs.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and library changes in Ruby 3.0 as well.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.1 was released on 25 December 2021.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It includes YJIT, a new, experimental, Just-In-Time Compiler developed by Shopify, to enhance the performance of real world business applications.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] There are some syntax enhancements and other improvements in this release.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Network libraries for FTP, SMTP, IMAP, and POP are moved from default gems to bundled gems.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.2 was released on 25 December 2022.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It brings support for being run inside of a WebAssembly environment via a WASI interface.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Regular expressions also receives some improvements, including a faster, memoized matching algorithm to protect against certain ReDoS attacks, and configurable timeouts for regular expression matching.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Additional debugging and syntax features are also included in this release, which include syntax suggestion, as well as error highlighting.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The MJIT compiler has been re-implemented as a standard library module, while the YJIT, a Rust-based JIT compiler now supports more architectures on Linux.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 was released on 25 December 2023.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.3 introduces significant enhancements and performance improvements to the language.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Key features include the introduction of the Prism parser for portable and maintainable parsing, the addition of the pure-Ruby JIT compiler RJIT, and major performance boosts in the YJIT compiler.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Additionally, improvements in memory usage, the introduction of an M:N thread scheduler, and updates to the standard library contribute to a more efficient and developer-friendly Ruby ecosystem.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 was released on 25 December 2024.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby 3.4 adds `it` block parameter reference, changes Prism as default parser, adds Happy Eyeballs Version 2 support to socket library, improves YJIT, adds modular Garbage Collector and so on.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It adds experimental ZJIT, a JIT written in Rust, and experimental "Ruby Box", a feature to provide separation about definitions.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It was decided to bump the version number to 4.0 instead of 3.5 to celebrate Rubys 30. birthday.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto stated that Ruby is designed for programmer productivity and fun, following the principles of good user interface design.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] At a Google Tech Talk in 2008 he said, "I hope to see Ruby help every programmer in the world to be productive, and to enjoy programming, and to be happy.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto has said his primary design goal was to make a language that he himself enjoyed using, by minimizing programmer work and possible confusion.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] If that personal standard remains consistent, there would be few surprises for those familiar with the standard.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is object-oriented: every value is an object, including classes and instances of types that many other languages designate as primitives (such as integers, Booleans, and "null").
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Because everything in Ruby is an object, everything in Ruby has certain built-in abilities called methods.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Every function is a method and methods are always called on an object.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Methods defined at the top level scope become methods of the Object class.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Since this class is an ancestor of every other class, such methods can be called on any object.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] They are also visible in all scopes, effectively serving as "global" procedures.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby supports inheritance with dynamic dispatch, mixins and singleton methods (belonging to, and defined for, a single instance rather than being defined on the class).
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Though Ruby does not support multiple inheritance, classes can import modules as mixins.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] It has support for introspection, reflective programming, metaprogramming, and interpreter-based threads.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby features dynamic typing, and supports parametric polymorphism.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] According to the Ruby FAQ, the syntax is similar to Perl's and the semantics are similar to Smalltalk's, but the design philosophy differs greatly from Python's.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The syntax of Ruby is broadly similar to that of Perl and Python.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Class and method definitions are signaled by keywords, whereas code blocks can be defined by either keywords or braces.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] In contrast to Perl, variables are not obligatorily prefixed with a sigil.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] When used, the sigil changes the semantics of scope of the variable.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] For practical purposes there is no distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Line breaks are significant and taken as the end of a statement; a semicolon may be equivalently used.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Unlike Python, indentation is not significant.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] One of the differences from Python and Perl is that Ruby keeps all of its instance variables completely private to the class and only exposes them through accessor methods (`attr_writer`, `attr_reader`, etc.).
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Unlike the "getter" and "setter" methods of other languages like C++ or Java, accessor methods in Ruby can be created with a single line of code via metaprogramming; however, accessor methods can also be created in the traditional fashion of C++ and Java.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] As invocation of these methods does not require the use of parentheses, it is trivial to change an instance variable into a full function, without modifying a single line of calling code or having to do any refactoring achieving similar functionality to C# and VB.NET property members.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Python's property descriptors are similar, but come with a trade-off in the development process.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] If one begins in Python by using a publicly exposed instance variable, and later changes the implementation to use a private instance variable exposed through a property descriptor, code internal to the class may need to be adjusted to use the private variable rather than the public property.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby's design forces all instance variables to be private, but also provides a simple way to declare `set` and `get` methods.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] This is in keeping with the idea that in Ruby, one never directly accesses the internal members of a class from outside the class; rather, one passes a message to the class and receives a response.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The original Ruby interpreter is often referred to as Matz's Ruby Interpreter or MRI.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] This implementation is written in C and uses its own Ruby-specific virtual machine.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The standardized and retired Ruby 1.8 implementation was written in C, as a single-pass interpreted language.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Starting with Ruby 1.9, and continuing with Ruby 2.x and above, the official Ruby interpreter has been YARV ("Yet Another Ruby VM"), and this implementation has superseded the slower virtual machine used in previous releases of MRI.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] As of 2026, there are a number of alternative implementations of Ruby, including JRuby, Rubinius, and mruby.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Each takes a different approach, with JRuby and Rubinius providing just-in-time compilation and mruby also providing ahead-of-time compilation.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The maturity of Ruby implementations tends to be measured by their ability to run the Ruby on Rails (Rails) framework, because it is complex to implement and uses many Ruby-specific features.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The point when a particular implementation achieves this goal is called "the Rails singularity".
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The reference implementation, JRuby, and Rubinius are all able to run Rails unmodified in a production environment.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Matsumoto originally developed Ruby on the 4.3BSD-based Sony NEWS-OS 3.x, but later migrated his work to SunOS 4.x, and finally to Linux.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] By 1999, Ruby was known to work across many different operating systems.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Modern Ruby versions and implementations are available on all major desktop, mobile and server-based operating systems.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Ruby is also supported across a number of cloud hosting platforms like Jelastic, Heroku, Google Cloud Platform and others.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Tools such as RVM and RBEnv, facilitate installation and partitioning of multiple ruby versions, and multiple 'gemsets' on one machine.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] A Ruby package is called a "gem" and can be installed via the command line.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Most gems are libraries, though a few exist that are applications, such as IDEs.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] There are over 100,000 Ruby gems hosted on RubyGems.org.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] Many new and existing Ruby libraries are hosted on GitHub, a service that offers version control repository hosting for Git.
[src:roda-ruby/ruby-programming-language] The Ruby Application Archive, which hosted applications, documentation, and libraries for Ruby programming, was maintained until 2013, when its function was transferred to RubyGems.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] In computer science, a **tree** is a widely used abstract data type that represents a hierarchical tree structure with a set of connected nodes.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Each node in the tree can be connected to many children (depending on the type of tree), but must be connected to exactly one parent, except for the *root* node, which has no parent (i.e., the root node as the top-most node in the tree hierarchy).
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] These constraints mean there are no cycles or "loops" (no node can be its own ancestor), and also that each child can be treated like the root node of its own subtree, making recursion a useful technique for tree traversal.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] In contrast to linear data structures, many trees cannot be represented by relationships between neighboring nodes (parent and children nodes of a node under consideration, if they exist) in a single straight line (called edge or link between two adjacent nodes).
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Binary trees are a commonly used type, which constrain the number of children for each parent to at most two.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] When the order of the children is specified, this data structure corresponds to an ordered tree in graph theory.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] A value or pointer to other data may be associated with every node in the tree, or sometimes only with the *leaf nodes*, which have no children nodes.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] The abstract data type (ADT) can be represented in a number of ways, including a list of parents with pointers to children, a list of children with pointers to parents, or a list of nodes and a separate list of parent-child relations (a specific type of adjacency list).
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Representations might also be more complicated, for example using indexes or ancestor lists for performance.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Trees as used in computing are similar to but can be different from mathematical constructs of trees in graph theory, trees in set theory, and trees in descriptive set theory.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] A node is a structure which may contain data and connections to other nodes, sometimes called **edges** or **links**.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Each node in a tree has zero or more **child nodes**, which are below it in the tree (by convention, trees are drawn with *descendants* going downwards).
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] A node that has a child is called the child's **parent node** (or superior).
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] All nodes have exactly one parent, except the topmost **root node**, which has none.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] A node might have many **ancestor nodes**, such as the parent's parent.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Child nodes with the same parent are **sibling nodes**.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Typically siblings have an order, with the first one conventionally drawn on the left.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Some definitions allow a tree to have no nodes at all, in which case it is called *empty*.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] An **internal node** (also known as an **inner node**, **inode** for short, or **branch node**) is any node of a tree that has child nodes.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Similarly, an **external node** (also known as an **outer node**, **leaf node**, or **terminal node**) is any node that does not have child nodes.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] The **height** of a node is the length of the longest downward path to a leaf from that node.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] The height of the root is the height of the tree.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] The **depth** of a node is the length of the path to its root (i.e., its *root path*).
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Thus the root node has depth zero, leaf nodes have height zero, and a tree with only a single node (hence both a root and leaf) has depth and height zero.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Conventionally, an empty tree (tree with no nodes, if such are allowed) has height −1.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Each non-root node can be treated as the root node of its own **subtree**, which includes that node and all its descendants.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] A node reachable by repeated proceeding from child to parent.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] A node reachable by repeated proceeding from parent to child.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] For a given node, its number of children.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] The degree of a tree is the maximum degree of a node in the tree.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] The number of edges along the shortest path between two nodes.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] The level of a node is the number of edges along the unique path between it and the root node.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] A tree with every level filled, except the last.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] A rooted tree in which an ordering is specified for the children of each vertex.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Stepping through the items of a tree, by means of the connections between parents and children, is called **walking the tree**, and the action is a *walk* of the tree.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Often, an operation might be performed when a pointer arrives at a particular node.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] There are many different ways to represent trees.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] In working memory, nodes are typically dynamically allocated records with pointers to their children, their parents, or both, as well as any associated data.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] If of a fixed size, the nodes might be stored in a list.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Nodes and relationships between nodes might be stored in a separate special type of adjacency list.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] In relational databases, nodes are typically represented as table rows, with indexed row IDs facilitating pointers between parents and children.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Nodes can also be stored as items in an array, with relationships between them determined by their positions in the array (as in a binary heap).
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] A binary tree can be implemented as a list of lists: the head of a list (the value of the first term) is the left child (subtree), while the tail (the list of second and subsequent terms) is the right child (subtree).
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] This can be modified to allow values as well, as in Lisp S-expressions, where the head (value of first term) is the value of the node, the head of the tail (value of second term) is the left child, and the tail of the tail (list of third and subsequent terms) is the right child.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Ordered trees can be naturally encoded by finite sequences, for example with natural numbers.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] 4 has more than one parent (inbound edge).
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] B has more than one parent (inbound edge).
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] In terms of type theory, a tree is an inductive type defined by the constructors nil (empty forest) and node (tree with root node with given value and children).
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Viewed as a whole, a tree data structure is an ordered tree, generally with values attached to each node.
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Often trees have a fixed (more properly, bounded) branching factor (outdegree), particularly always having two child nodes (possibly empty, hence *at most* two *non-empty* child nodes), hence a "binary tree".
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] Allowing empty trees makes some definitions simpler, some more complicated: a rooted tree must be non-empty, hence if empty trees are allowed the above definition instead becomes "an empty tree or a rooted tree such that ...".
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] On the other hand, empty trees simplify defining fixed branching factor: with empty trees allowed, a binary tree is a tree such that every node has exactly two children, each of which is a tree (possibly empty).
[src:roda-ruby/tree-abstract-data-type] JSON and YAML documents can be thought of as trees, but are typically represented by nested lists and dictionaries.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:roda-ruby/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
